#T_SP=de.tudarmstadt.ukp.dkpro.core.api.ner.type.NamedEntity|identifier|value
#Text=### Vertex-Enriched Graph Neural Network (VEGNN)   This is my work directory of our submission to Machine Learning Journal.
#Text=The work is based on the Vertex-Enrichment process of Graph Neural Networks.
#Text=That is: augmenting the node features with relational-features obtained by using symbolic domain-knowledge.
#Text=We treat these symbolic relations as hyperedges meaning any relation or a relational feature is a hyperedge.
#Text=For more information on this, please go through our paper.
#Text=We will be updating new experiments that we have conducted (or will conduct) in some other repository.

#Text=We shall update this README accordingly.   #### Machine, Tools and Requirements  Machine specification:    \* `Machine: Dell 5810`   \* `RAM: 64GB`   \* `Processor: Intel 16-Core Xeon (3.10GHz)`   \* `GPU: NVIDIA P4000 (8GB VRAM)`   \* `OS: Ubuntu Linux 16.04.6 LTS (64bit)`  Tools used in this work:    \* `Editor: vi/vim`   \* `Execution: Linux-Shell`   \* `MATLAB R2018b (64bit)`   \* `Prolog compiler: YAP 6.2.2`   \* `ILP Engine: Aleph`   \* `CUDA 10.1.105`   \* `Python 3.7.6`  Python Libraries:     \* `torch 1.4.0`   \* `torch\_geometric 1.2.1`   \* `numpy 1.18.1`   #### Source Data  There are 73 problems obtained from NCI.
#Text=The data source including the extracted domain relations will be made available somewhere else (non-GitHub site) due to storage issues.
#Text=Temporarity, this is hosted in the Google Drive: \[DataForVEGNN\](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1eJrq\_kvD2UmWiWe6F3C3Ire0fbv6CNrm/view?
#Text=usp=sharing).
#Text=The compressed file contains all data required for the work.
#Text=Soon, we should be able to host these generated datasets with some well-known Benchmark websites.
#Text=The information will be updated in this site, when that happens.   #### Working Data directory  A temporary data directory is created in `.
#Text=/data`.
#Text=Under this there are two two directories for processing: `.
#Text=/data/raw` and `.
#Text=/data/processed`.
#Text=Purposefully, the files are kept empty for uploading to GitHub.
#Text=The split information gets copied to `.
#Text=/data/train\_split` and `.
#Text=/data/test\_split`.   #### Shell scripts  The script "run.bash" is one-shot execution of all methods
#Text=.
#Text=` bash run.bash `  The script "resultsummary.bash" summarises the results for each dataset.
#Text=For this, one needs to supply the result directory as an argument.

#Text=For example:  ` bash resultsummary.bash Result\_dir\_name `  To store the results in a file:  ` bash resultsummary.bash Result\_dir\_name > Result\_file\_name.txt `  To store only dataset and accuracy, one can \*gawk\* out the columns and then redirect to some file.
#Text=\*\*added 1:\*\* One can now create a full summary with regard to all the datasets and features for any particular method.
#Text=See the following for help about the new summarising script
#Text=.

#Text=` bash createressum.bash --help `   \*\*added 2:\*\* Added a Python script to load a (trained) saved model and print the structure  ` python modelsummary.py `  \*\*added 3:\*\* Code to load the saved models for deployment.
#Text=Deployment refers to testing the trained model on unseen data.
#Text=For us this is: test data.
#Text=Added also the printing model code in this.
#Text=So, no need to explicitly use the modelsummary.py code given in "added 2"
#Text=.
#Text=` bash test.bash `  Some results from this are saved in the file `testedsavedmodels.out`.
#Text=\*\*added 4:\*\* The `createressum\_\*.bash` files summarise the results
#Text=.
#Text=` bash createressum\_\[enter\].bash --help `   #### Note on Reproducibility   The implementations have been carried out using \[PyTorch\](https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/index.html).
#Text=All the experiments are conducted by setting a fixed seed for the Random Number Generator (RNG).

#Text=Although we believe that this should be sufficient to reproduce all the experiments\; we note the \[official statement\](https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/notes/randomness.html) from PyTorch on reproducibility: "Completely reproducible results are not guaranteed across PyTorch releases, individual commits or different platforms.
